    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey prof, i'm stuck on this concept for my midterm. can u give me a real world example of opportunity cost? like, if a company has to choose between buying new machinery for a factory or spending that money on a big marketing campaign, how does opportunity cost work there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, let's take a look at that scenario. Imagine a company, let's call it \"GizmoCorp,\" which has a choice between buying new machinery for their factory or spending the same amount of money on a big marketing campaign. The opportunity cost here is the value of the next best alternative that they forego when they make their decision. If GizmoCorp decides to buy the new machinery, the opportunity cost would be the potential increase in sales and brand awareness that the marketing campaign could have provided. Conversely, if they choose the marketing campaign, the opportunity cost would be the increased production efficiency and potential cost savings from the new machinery. In essence, the company must weigh these alternatives and determine which option will yield the highest return on investment.",
